1) There is a relationship between TV and Sales and Radio and Sales but there is no relationship between Newspaper and Sales because the p-value is very close to zero for both TV and Radio but close to 1 for Newspaper. The null hypothesis for the p-value for TV is that the coefficient is zero and the p-value says that getting a value of .046 is so rare that it is unlikely to have happened if the null hypothesis is true. The same applies for radio and newspaper but for newspaper the p-value is higher and it is likely for that the coefficient value to have occured if the null hypothesis is true.

r set.seed(1) x1=runif (100) x2=0.5*x1+rnorm (100)/10 y=2+2*x1+0.3*x2+rnorm (100) The regression coefficients are Bnot = 2, B1=2, and B2=.3
B)

r plot(x1 ~ x2)

The correlation appears to be linear between x1 and x2
C)

r plot(x1 ~ x2) abline(lm(x1~x2))

Bnot is 2.13, B1= 1.44, B2=1.01. These B values are different from the true values where Bnot = 2, B1=2, and B2=.3. You can reject the null hypothesis for B1 because the p-value is .049. You cant reject the null hypothesis for B2.
D)

r plot(y ~ x1) abline(lm(y ~ x1))

You can reject the null hypothesis because the p-value is so small.
E)

r plot(y ~ x2) abline(lm(y ~ x2))

You can reject the null hypothesis because the p-value is so small. F) Yes the seem to contradict each other because you can reject the null hypothesis for x2 when it is regressed against y by itself but not when it is regressed with x1 against y.
G) For lm(y~x1 + x2) you can reject the null hypothesis for x2 but not for x1.
For lm(y~x1) you can reject the null hypothesis for x1
For lm(y~x2) you can reject the null hypothesis for x2
